text: [Ace.pdf - page 1] Ace â€“ Paracetamol Brand name: Ace Generic name: Paracetamol BP Manufacturer: Square Pharmaceuticals PLC Dosage forms: Tablet, syrup, suspension, paediatric drops, suppository, IV infusion Composition Ace products contain Paracetamol BP in a range of strengths and dosage forms, including tablets, syrup, suspension, paediatric drops, suppositories and IV infusion. Pharmacology Paracetamol is an analgesic and antipyretic. It produces analgesia by elevation of the pain threshold and antipyresis by action on the hypothalamic heat-regulating centre. It has minimal anti-inflammatory activity at recommended doses. Indication Used for relief of fever and for mild to moderate pain such as headache, common cold and influenza, toothache, bodyache and other painful conditions as advised by a physician. Usage Usage: fever, headache, body pain, toothache, common cold, influenza and other mild to moderate pain. Dosage and administration Dose and frequency depend on age, body weight and dosage form. Total daily dose must not exceed the recommended maximum for paracetamol. Use exactly as directed on the product label or by a physician. Contraindication Known hypersensitivity to paracetamol. Side effects Side effects are usually mild. Rarely, haematological reactions and skin rashes or other allergic reactions may occur.

[Ace.pdf - page 1] Rarely, haematological reactions and skin rashes or other allergic reactions may occur. Overdose Paracetamol overdose can cause severe, potentially fatal liver damage. Early symptoms include nausea, vomiting, anorexia and abdominal pain. In severe poisoning, hepatic failure may progress to encephalopathy, coma and death. Immediate medical attention is essential in all cases of suspected overdose.

[Ace.pdf - page 2] Use in pregnancy and lactation Paracetamol is generally considered compatible with pregnancy and breastfeeding at recommended doses, but should be used under medical advice. Storage Store in a cool, dry place, protected from light. Keep all medicines out of the reach of children. How supplied Ace products are supplied in various strengths and dosage forms. Individual packs contain different quantities as stated on the respective labels.

Composition - Tablet: Each tablet contains Paracetamol BP 500 mg. - Extended Release Tablet (XR): Each tablet contains Paracetamol BP 665 mg. - Syrup 60 ml: Each 5 ml syrup contains Paracetamol BP 120 mg. - Syrup 100 ml: Each 5 ml syrup contains Paracetamol BP 120 mg. - Suspension: Each 5 ml suspension contains Paracetamol BP 120 mg. - Paediatric Drop (15 ml): Each ml paediatric drop contains Paracetamol BP 80 mg. - Paediatric Drop (30 ml): Each ml paediatric drop contains Paracetamol BP 80 mg. - Suppository 60 mg: Each suppository contains Paracetamol BP 60 mg. - Suppository 125 mg: Each suppository contains Paracetamol BP 125 mg. - Suppository 250 mg: Each suppository contains Paracetamol BP 250 mg. - Suppository 500 mg: Each suppository contains Paracetamol BP 500 mg.

[Ace_XR.pdf - page 1] - Suppository 500 mg: Each suppository contains Paracetamol BP 500 mg. How this medicine works (pharmacology) Ace is a formulation of Paracetamol (Acetaminophen), which is one of the safest and most widely used analgesic and antipyretic agents. Paracetamol produces analgesia by elevating the pain threshold and antipyresis through action on the hypothalamic heat-regulating centre. At recommended doses, paracetamol has minimal effect on the cardiovascular and respiratory systems, and it does not cause gastric irritation or ulceration like many NSAIDs. Paracetamol is rapidly and almost completely absorbed from the gastrointestinal tract and is distributed into most body tissues. It is metabolised primarily in the liver and excreted in the urine mainly as glucuronide and sulphate conjugates. Only a small fraction is metabolised to a reactive intermediate which may cause liver damage in overdose.

[Ace_XR.pdf - page 2] Following rectal administration, absorption may be slower than from the stomach. The plasma half-life is approximately 1.5 to 3.0 hours in subjects with normal hepatic function. Indications - Relief of pain and fever associated with common cold, influenza and other viral or bacterial infections. - Headache, including migraine. - Toothache and teething pain. - Muscular pain, myalgia, backache, sprains and strains. - Dysmenorrhoea. - Post-operative pain. - Pain of osteoarthritis and rheumatoid arthritis as advised by a physician. - Pain and fever associated with vaccination. Dosage and administration The lowest effective dose should be used for the shortest duration necessary to relieve symptoms. Dose and frequency depend on age, body weight, dosage form and clinical response. Always follow the physicianâ€™s instructions and the information on the product label. - Adults and children over 12 years (tablet / XR tablet / oral liquid): Commonly 500â€“ 1000 mg every 4â€“6 hours as needed, without exceeding the maximum recommended daily dose printed on the pack. - Extended Release (Ace XR) tablets are designed for prolonged effect and should be swallowed whole with water; they must not be crushed, chewed or broken.

[Ace_XR.pdf - page 2] - Children: Dosage is based on body weight, usually 10â€“15 mg/kg per dose every 4â€“6 hours, up to the maximum number of doses per 24 hours as indicated in the leaflet. - Paediatric drops / syrup / suspension: Dose should be carefully measured using the supplied dropper or measuring cup. Age- and weight-specific recommendations are provided in the original dosage table. - Suppositories: Used when the oral route is not feasible; dosing follows standard paediatric and adult suppository regimens as detailed in the leaflet. Note: The original Ace leaflet contains a detailed weight-based and age-based dosage table for paediatric preparations and suppositories, which should be consulted for exact dosing. Contraindications & warnings - Known sensitivity or hypersensitivity to paracetamol or any component of the formulation. - Severe hepatic impairment or active liver disease. - Concomitant use with other paracetamol-containing products should be avoided to prevent overdose.

[Ace_XR.pdf - page 3] Precautions Use with caution in patients with impaired hepatic or renal function, chronic alcohol use, chronic malnutrition, dehydration or anaemia. Prolonged or frequent use at higher than recommended doses may increase the risk of liver damage. Patients should not take other paracetamol-containing medicines concurrently. If fever persists or pain does not improve within a few days, medical advice should be sought. Side effects Side effects are generally mild, though haematological reactions have been reported. Possible adverse reactions include: - Skin rashes and other allergic reactions, occasionally severe, including urticaria and angioedema. - Blood dyscrasias such as thrombocytopenia, leukopenia or neutropenia (rare). - Pancreatitis has been reported rarely, usually in association with liver dysfunction. Drug interactions Paracetamol may interact with other drugs, particularly those affecting hepatic enzymes. Enzyme-inducing drugs such as certain antiepileptics or rifampicin may increase formation of toxic metabolites and enhance risk of hepatotoxicity. Chronic alcohol use increases the risk of liver damage when combined with paracetamol. Use in pregnancy & lactation Paracetamol is commonly used during pregnancy and lactation and, when used at recommended doses, is generally considered safe.

[Ace_XR.pdf - page 3] As with all medicines, paracetamol should be used during pregnancy or breast-feeding only on medical advice and for the shortest duration necessary. Overdose Paracetamol overdose is a serious medical emergency. Early symptoms within 24 hours may include pallor, nausea, vomiting, anorexia and abdominal pain. Liver damage may become apparent 12â€“48 hours after ingestion and may lead to hepatic failure, encephalopathy, coma and death.

[Ace_XR.pdf - page 4] Management includes prompt gastric lavage when appropriate, measurement of plasma paracetamol concentration and administration of N-acetylcysteine according to established treatment guidelines, together with supportive and symptomatic care. Storage - Store below 30Â°C in a cool, dry place. - Protect from light and moisture. - Keep out of the reach of children. How supplied - Ace XR Extended Release Tablets: Supplied in blister packs (exact pack sizes as per marketed presentation). - Ace tablets, syrup, suspension, paediatric drops and suppositories: Supplied in various blister pack and bottle presentations as described on the individual packs. Usage Usage: fever, headache, migraine, toothache, body pain, muscular pain, post-vaccination fever, cold- and flu-related pain and fever.

[AcePlus.pdf - page 1] Ace Plus â€“ Paracetamol & Caffeine Brand name: Ace Plus Generic name: Paracetamol BP 500 mg and Caffeine BP 65 mg Manufacturer: Square Pharmaceuticals PLC Dosage form: Tablet Composition Each Ace Plus tablet contains Paracetamol BP 500 mg and Caffeine BP 65 mg. Pharmacology Ace Plus combines paracetamol, an analgesic and antipyretic, with caffeine, a mild central nervous system stimulant. Caffeine can enhance the analgesic effect of paracetamol and helps relieve headache and migraine. Indication Indicated for fever, headache, migraine, muscle ache, backache, toothache and menstrual pain. Usage Usage: fever, headache, migraine, muscle pain, back pain, toothache, menstrual pain. Dosage and administration Adults: 1â€“2 tablets every 4â€“6 hours as needed. Maximum 8 tablets in 24 hours. Not recommended for children under 12 years. Use the lowest effective dose for the shortest duration necessary. Contraindication - Hypersensitivity to paracetamol, caffeine or any component of the product. Side effects This combination may cause skin rashes, neutropenia and gastrointestinal disturbances. High-dose or prolonged use may increase the risk of hepatotoxicity, particularly in patients with pre-existing liver disease or in alcoholics.

[AcePlus.pdf - page 1] High-dose or prolonged use may increase the risk of hepatotoxicity, particularly in patients with pre-existing liver disease or in alcoholics. Pregnancy and lactation Epidemiological studies generally support the safety of paracetamol in pregnancy and lactation, but medical advice should be sought before using this combination. Caffeine intake should be limited during pregnancy and breastfeeding.

[AcePlus.pdf - page 2] Drug interaction Paracetamol may increase the effect of chloramphenicol and coumarin anticoagulants. Risk of hepatotoxicity is increased in patients taking other hepatotoxic drugs or consuming alcohol. Precaution Use with caution in patients with liver disease, in those taking other paracetamol- containing products or hepatotoxic drugs, and in individuals sensitive to caffeine. Prolonged use without medical supervision is not recommended. Storage Store in a cool, dry place, protected from light and moisture. Keep out of reach of children. How supplied Ace Plus tablet: each box contains 200 tablets in blister pack.

[Adovas.pdf - page 1] Adovas â€“ Herbal Cough Syrup Brand and generic name Brand name: Adovas Generic name: Polyherbal cough preparation (e.g. Vasaka, Tulsi, Licorice, Ginger and other herbal extracts). Manufacturer: Square Pharmaceuticals PLC Dosage form: Syrup Composition Adovas is a herbal cough syrup containing a combination of plant extracts traditionally used to relieve cough, throat irritation and respiratory discomfort. The exact composition and quantity of each herbal extract are listed on the product label. How this medicine works (pharmacology) The herbal ingredients of Adovas possess demulcent, expectorant and mild bronchodilatory properties. They help to soothe the irritated mucosa of the respiratory tract, reduce throat irritation and facilitate expectoration of mucus. Some components may have mild anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial activity, contributing to relief of symptoms associated with cough and cold. Indications - Cough of various causes, including cough associated with common cold. - Throat irritation and hoarseness of voice. - As an adjunct in upper respiratory tract infections where soothing of the throat and facilitation of mucus clearance are desired. Dosage and administration Dosage should follow the recommendations on the product label or as directed by a physician. - Adults: Commonly 2 teaspoonfuls three times daily.

[Adovas.pdf - page 1] - Adults: Commonly 2 teaspoonfuls three times daily. - Children: Commonly 1 teaspoonful three times daily or as advised by the physician. - Shake the bottle well before use. - If symptoms persist, medical advice should be sought.

[Adovas.pdf - page 2] Contraindications & warnings - Hypersensitivity to any of the herbal ingredients in the formulation. - Use with caution in patients with known allergy to herbal products. - Patients with persistent or chronic cough (e.g. due to asthma, smoking, chronic bronchitis) should seek medical advice before use. Precautions Use with caution in patients with diabetes, depending on the sugar content of the syrup. If cough persists for more than a week, recurs or is accompanied by fever, rash or persistent headache, medical evaluation is necessary. Children, pregnant women and lactating mothers should use this product only on a physician's advice. Side effects Adovas is generally well tolerated. Possible adverse reactions include: - Mild gastrointestinal discomfort in sensitive individuals. - Allergic reactions such as rash, itching or urticaria in patients sensitive to any herbal component. Drug interactions No specific drug interactions have been documented. However, as with all herbal products, patients should inform their physician about all other medications they are taking. Use in pregnancy & lactation Safety of Adovas during pregnancy and lactation has not been established in controlled clinical studies. Use during pregnancy and breastfeeding should be based on medical advice and a careful riskâ€“benefit assessment. Overdose Accidental overdose may increase the risk of gastrointestinal discomfort or other adverse reactions related to the herbal ingredients. Management is symptomatic and supportive.

[ADRYL.pdf - page 1] Adryl â€“ Diphenhydramine Hydrochloride Brand and generic name Brand name: Adryl Generic name: Diphenhydramine Hydrochloride BP Manufacturer: Square Pharmaceuticals PLC Dosage form: Syrup Composition Each 5 ml of Adryl syrup contains Diphenhydramine Hydrochloride BP 10 mg. How this medicine works (pharmacology) Diphenhydramine is a first-generation antihistamine with potent H1-receptor blocking activity and significant anticholinergic and sedative properties. It is well absorbed from the gastrointestinal tract and widely distributed throughout the body, including the central nervous system. It is used for its antihistaminic, antitussive, antiemetic, antispasmodic and antiparkinsonian effects. Indications Adryl is indicated for the treatment of: - Seasonal, perennial and vasomotor rhinitis. - Urticaria, angioneurotic oedema and as an adjunct in anaphylaxis. - Pruritus. - Pre-anaesthetic medication, emesis and motion sickness. - Meniereâ€™s disease and as adjunctive therapy in parkinsonism. - Cough and cold. - Short-term management of insomnia and as a night-time sleep aid (where appropriate).

[ADRYL.pdf - page 1] - Cough and cold. - Short-term management of insomnia and as a night-time sleep aid (where appropriate). Dosage and administration General allergic conditions: - Adults: 25â€“50 mg (12.5â€“25 ml) three to four times daily. - Children 1â€“6 years: 5 mg (2.5 ml) three to four times daily. - Children over 6 years: 10 mg (5 ml) three to four times daily. - Maximum daily dose: not to exceed 300 mg in adults and children. Specific regimens for motion sickness, parkinsonism, insomnia and cough/cold should follow the original product recommendations and physicianâ€™s advice.

[ADRYL.pdf - page 2] Contraindications & warnings - Premature or newborn infants. - Patients in whom drowsiness is undesirable (e.g. drivers, machine operators). - Concomitant intake of alcohol or other CNS depressants. - Known hypersensitivity to diphenhydramine or any component of the formulation. Precautions Patients should be cautioned not to drive, operate machinery or perform tasks requiring mental alertness until they know how Adryl affects them. Use with caution in patients with glaucoma, urinary retention, prostatic hypertrophy, cardiovascular disease or severe hepatic impairment. Side effects Possible adverse reactions include: - Drowsiness, dizziness. - Dry mouth. - Blurred vision. - Nausea and vomiting. - Other anticholinergic effects. Drug interactions - Reduces absorption of para-aminosalicylic acid (PAS). - Has additive CNS depressant effects with alcohol, hypnotics, sedatives and tranquilisers. - Monoamine oxidase (MAO) inhibitors may prolong and intensify the anticholinergic effects. Use in pregnancy & lactation There are no adequate, well-controlled studies in pregnant women; diphenhydramine should be used during pregnancy only if clearly needed. Diphenhydramine is excreted in breast milk; use in lactating mothers is not recommended.

[ADRYL.pdf - page 2] Diphenhydramine is excreted in breast milk; use in lactating mothers is not recommended. Overdose Overdosage may lead to central nervous system depression or stimulation, the latter especially in children. Atropine-like signs such as dry mouth, fixed dilated pupils and flushing, as well as gastrointestinal symptoms may occur. Management is symptomatic and supportive. Storage - Store below 30Â°C. - Protect from light. - Keep out of the reach of children.

[ADRYL.pdf - page 3] How supplied Adryl syrup: PET or glass bottles containing 50 ml, 60 ml or 100 ml syrup with a measuring cup. Usage Usage: allergy symptoms (runny nose, sneezing, itching), cough, cold, motion sickness, nausea, itching, trouble sleeping (short-term, as directed).

[ALATROL.pdf - page 1] Alatrol â€“ Cetirizine Hydrochloride Brand and generic name Brand name: Alatrol Generic name: Cetirizine Hydrochloride BP Manufacturer: Square Pharmaceuticals PLC Dosage forms: Tablet, syrup, paediatric drops Composition - Tablet: Cetirizine Hydrochloride BP 10 mg. - Syrup (per 5 ml): Cetirizine Hydrochloride BP 5 mg. - Paediatric drops (per 1 ml): Cetirizine Hydrochloride BP 2.5 mg. How this medicine works (pharmacology) Cetirizine is a potent and selective peripheral H1-receptor antagonist with minimal anticholinergic and antiserotonergic effects. At recommended doses, it produces little or no sedation and does not usually cause behavioural changes, likely due to limited penetration across the bloodâ€“brain barrier. Cetirizine inhibits the early phase of the allergic reaction and reduces cell migration and mediator release in the late phase. It is rapidly absorbed, with a plasma half-life of about 6.7â€“10.9 hours. Indications - Seasonal allergic rhinitis: relief of sneezing, rhinorrhoea, nasal and ocular pruritus, tearing and redness due to pollens.

[ALATROL.pdf - page 1] - Perennial allergic rhinitis: due to dust, mites, animal dander and moulds. - Chronic idiopathic urticaria: reduces occurrence, severity and duration of hives and pruritus. - Adjunct in allergen-induced asthma. Dosage and administration Alatrol may be taken with or without food. - Adults and children â‰¥6 years: 10 mg (1 tablet or 10 ml syrup) once daily, or 5 ml syrup twice daily. - Children 2â€“6 years: 5 ml syrup once daily or 2.5 ml twice daily. - Children 6 months to <2 years: 2.5 ml syrup once daily; in 12â€“23 months, may increase to 2.5 ml twice daily, or 1 ml paediatric drops once or twice daily as recommended. - Renal impairment (creatinine clearance 11â€“31 ml/min), haemodialysis (ClCr <7 ml/min) and hepatic impairment: 5 mg (Â½ tablet) or 5 ml syrup once daily.

[ALATROL.pdf - page 2] Contraindications & warnings - Known hypersensitivity or idiosyncrasy to cetirizine, hydroxyzine or any component of the formulation. Precautions Use with caution when driving, operating machinery or performing tasks requiring mental alertness. Avoid concurrent use with alcohol or other central nervous system depressants, which may cause additional reduction in alertness and performance. Side effects Cetirizine has a low incidence of sedation; rates are comparable to placebo and other non- sedating antihistamines and lower than many first-generation antihistamines. It does not exhibit clinically significant anticholinergic effects at recommended doses. Drug interactions No clinically significant drug interactions have been observed with theophylline, azithromycin, pseudoephedrine, ketoconazole, erythromycin or other commonly co- administered medicines at usual doses. Use in pregnancy & lactation - Pregnancy category B. Use during pregnancy only if clearly needed. - Cetirizine is excreted in human milk; use in lactating mothers is not recommended. Overdose Limited information is available. Overdosage may be expected to cause drowsiness in adults and, in some cases, excitation in children. Management is symptomatic and supportive. Storage - Tablet: store below 30Â°C, protect from light and moisture.

[Ambrox.pdf - page 1] Ambrox â€“ Ambroxol Hydrochloride Brand and generic name Brand name: Ambrox Generic name: Ambroxol Hydrochloride Manufacturer: Square Pharmaceuticals PLC Dosage forms: Paediatric drops, syrup, sustained-release (SR) capsule. Composition - Paediatric Drops: Each 1 ml contains Ambroxol Hydrochloride BP 6 mg. - Syrup: Each 5 ml contains Ambroxol Hydrochloride BP 15 mg. - SR Capsule: Each sustained-release capsule contains Ambroxol Hydrochloride BP 75 mg. How this medicine works (pharmacology) Ambroxol is the active N-desmethyl metabolite of bromhexine and has mucokinetic and secretolytic properties. It enhances the production of serous bronchial secretions and decreases the viscosity of sputum by depolymerising mucopolysaccharide fibres. Ambroxol also stimulates the production and release of pulmonary surfactant, improving mucociliary clearance and enhancing gas exchange. These actions facilitate expectoration, reduce the frequency and severity of coughing, and improve breathing in patients with productive cough. Indications - Acute and chronic respiratory diseases associated with abnormal mucus secretion and impaired mucus transport. - Acute exacerbation of chronic bronchitis and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) when increased mucus production is present.

[Ambrox.pdf - page 1] - Other conditions of the upper and lower respiratory tract where facilitation of mucus clearance is desirable, as advised by a physician. Dosage and administration Dosage should be adjusted according to age, body weight and clinical response. Use as directed by the physician. - Paediatric drops (0â€“2 years): 0.5 ml two to three times daily or as directed. - Syrup 2â€“5 years: Â½â€“1 teaspoonful (2.5â€“5 ml) two to three times daily. - Syrup over 5 years: 1 teaspoonful (5 ml) two to three times daily.

[Ambrox.pdf - page 2] - SR Capsule: Adults and children over 12 years: 1 capsule once daily, preferably after food. - Duration of treatment depends on the nature and severity of the illness and should be determined by the physician. Contraindications & warnings - Known hypersensitivity to Ambroxol, bromhexine or to any of the excipients. - Use with caution in patients with a history of peptic ulcer disease. - If symptoms do not improve or worsen, medical advice should be sought. Precautions Use with caution in patients with severe hepatic or renal impairment; dose adjustment or longer dosing intervals may be required. Caution is advised in children, particularly when using the drops or syrup, and treatment should be supervised by a physician. Adequate fluid intake is recommended during therapy to support the mucolytic effect. Side effects Ambrox is generally well tolerated at recommended doses. Reported adverse reactions include: - Gastrointestinal disturbances such as epigastric pain, nausea, vomiting or diarrhoea. - Dyspepsia or abdominal discomfort. - Allergic reactions including rash, urticaria, pruritus and very rarely angioedema. - Rare cases of dry mouth or altered taste. Drug interactions No clinically significant interactions have been reported with Ambroxol at recommended doses.

[Ambrox.pdf - page 2] Drug interactions No clinically significant interactions have been reported with Ambroxol at recommended doses. Ambroxol may be administered concomitantly with commonly used antibiotics, such as amoxicillin, cefuroxime or erythromycin, without relevant pharmacokinetic interaction. As with all medicines, patients should inform their physician of all concomitant medications. Use in pregnancy & lactation Pregnancy: Animal studies have not demonstrated teratogenic effects, but adequate, well- controlled studies in pregnant women are lacking. As a precaution, Ambrox should be avoided in the first trimester and used with caution thereafter only if the expected benefit justifies the potential risk.

[Ambrox.pdf - page 3] Lactation: Ambroxol is excreted in small amounts in breast milk. Although no adverse effects in breast-fed infants are expected at therapeutic doses, caution is advised and use should be based on a riskâ€“benefit assessment by the physician. Overdose No specific symptoms of overdose have been described. In the event of significant overdose, symptoms may be limited to gastrointestinal disturbances such as nausea, vomiting or diarrhoea. Treatment is symptomatic and supportive. Gastric lavage may be considered shortly after ingestion of a large amount. Vital signs should be monitored. Storage - Store in a cool, dry place, away from direct light and moisture. - Keep out of the reach of children. - Do not use after the expiry date printed on the pack. How supplied - Ambrox Paediatric Drops: 15 ml bottle with calibrated dropper. - Ambrox Syrup: 100 ml bottle. - Ambrox SR Capsule: Box containing 30 capsules in blister packs. Usage Usage: productive cough, chest congestion, thick mucus, bronchitis, mucus-related breathing difficulty.

[Brofex.pdf - page 1] Brofex â€“ Dextromethorphan Hydrobromide Brand and generic name Brand name: Brofex Generic name: Dextromethorphan Hydrobromide USP Manufacturer: Square Pharmaceuticals PLC Dosage form: Syrup Composition - Each 5 ml of Brofex syrup contains Dextromethorphan Hydrobromide USP 10 mg, in a flavoured syrup base. How this medicine works (pharmacology) Dextromethorphan is a non-opioid antitussive agent structurally related to the opioids but lacking their analgesic and addictive properties at therapeutic doses. It acts centrally on the cough centre in the medulla to elevate the threshold for coughing, thereby reducing the frequency and intensity of coughing. At usual doses, it has little or no effect on respiratory function and causes much less sedation than many opioid antitussives. Indications - Symptomatic relief of dry, irritating, non-productive cough. - Cough associated with minor upper respiratory tract infections, common cold or inhaled irritants when suppression of cough is clinically desirable. Dosage and administration Dosage should be adjusted according to age and clinical response. Use as directed by the physician and do not exceed recommended doses. - Adults and children over 12 years: 10 ml every 6 hours as needed.

[Brofex.pdf - page 1] - Adults and children over 12 years: 10 ml every 6 hours as needed. - Children 6â€“12 years: 5 ml every 6 hours as needed. - Children 2â€“6 years: 2.5 ml every 6 hours as needed, only on medical advice. - Not recommended in children below 2 years of age except on the advice of a physician. - Dose intervals should not be shorter than 4 hours. Do not exceed the maximum daily dose advised by the physician. Contraindications & warnings - Hypersensitivity to dextromethorphan or any component of the formulation.

[Brofex.pdf - page 2] - Concomitant use with monoamine oxidase inhibitors (MAOIs) or within 14 days of stopping an MAOI due to risk of serious interactions including serotonin syndrome. - Patients with chronic productive cough associated with excessive secretions, such as in asthma, chronic bronchitis or emphysema, unless directed by a physician. - Caution in patients with significant respiratory depression. Precautions Use with caution in patients with impaired hepatic function, as dextromethorphan is metabolised in the liver. Persistent cough lasting more than a week, or accompanied by fever, rash or persistent headache, may be a sign of a serious condition; medical evaluation should be sought. Dextromethorphan may cause mild dizziness or drowsiness in some individuals; patients should be advised not to drive or operate machinery if affected. Caution is advised when used in combination with other centrally acting drugs. Side effects Brofex is generally well tolerated at recommended doses. Possible adverse effects include: - Mild dizziness or drowsiness. - Gastrointestinal discomfort, nausea or vomiting. - Occasionally abdominal pain or diarrhoea. - Skin rash or hypersensitivity reactions in susceptible individuals. - At high doses or in overdose, CNS symptoms such as excitation, confusion or disorientation may occur.

[Brofex.pdf - page 2] - At high doses or in overdose, CNS symptoms such as excitation, confusion or disorientation may occur. Drug interactions The following interactions should be considered: - Monoamine oxidase inhibitors (MAOIs): Risk of serious, sometimes fatal reactions including serotonin syndrome; concomitant use is contraindicated. - Other serotonergic agents (e.g. SSRIs, certain antidepressants): Potential increased risk of serotonin syndrome, especially at high doses. - CNS depressants such as alcohol, sedatives, hypnotics or tranquillizers: May enhance CNS effects such as dizziness or drowsiness. Use in pregnancy & lactation Pregnancy: There are no adequate, well-controlled studies in pregnant women. Dextromethorphan should only be used during pregnancy if the potential benefit justifies the potential risk to the fetus. Lactation: It is not known whether dextromethorphan is excreted in human breast milk. Caution is advised when administering to nursing mothers; use only on medical advice.

Rosuvastatin reduces LDL production and the number of LDL particles.

[Rosuva_EZ.pdf - page 1] Rosuvastatin reduces LDL production and the number of LDL particles. Ezetimibe reduces blood cholesterol by inhibiting the absorption of cholesterol by the small intestine. Its molecular target is a sterol transporter that is involved in intestinal uptake of cholesterol and phytosterols. The complementary mechanisms of rosuvastatin (reduced synthesis and increased clearance) and ezetimibe (reduced intestinal absorption) contribute to effective LDL- cholesterol lowering. Indications Rosuvastatin and Ezetimibe combination is indicated in adults: - As an adjunct to diet in patients with primary non-familial hyperlipidaemia to reduce low-density lipoprotein cholesterol (LDL-C). - Alone or as an adjunct to other LDL-C-lowering therapies in patients with homozygous familial hypercholesterolaemia (HoFH) to reduce LDL-C. Dosage and administration The dosage range of Rosuva EZ is 5/10 mg to 40/10 mg orally once a day.

[Rosuva_EZ.pdf - page 2] The recommended dosage depends on the indication, baseline LDL-C and individual risk for cardiovascular events. Patients with severe renal impairment (not on haemodialysis): initiate at 5 mg/10 mg once daily; do not exceed 10 mg/10 mg once daily. Tablets should be swallowed whole and should not be crushed, dissolved or chewed. Administer Rosuva EZ at least 2 hours before or 4 hours after administration of a bile acid sequestrant. Administer Rosuva EZ at least 2 hours before administration of an aluminium and magnesium hydroxide combination antacid. Contraindications & warnings - Active liver disease or decompensated cirrhosis. - Hypersensitivity to any component of Rosuva EZ. - Use in pregnancy and in women who may become pregnant. - Breastfeeding (see special population section). Precautions Myopathy and rhabdomyolysis: risk factors include age 65 years or greater, uncontrolled hypothyroidism, renal impairment, concomitant use with certain other drugs and higher Rosuva EZ dosages. Discontinue Rosuva EZ if markedly elevated creatine kinase (CK) levels occur or myopathy is diagnosed or suspected. Temporarily discontinue Rosuva EZ in patients experiencing an acute or serious condition at high risk of developing renal failure secondary to rhabdomyolysis.

[Rosuva_EZ.pdf - page 2] Hepatic dysfunction: increases in serum transaminases have occurred, some persistent. Rare reports of fatal and non-fatal hepatic failure have been reported; consider liver enzyme testing before initiating therapy and as clinically indicated thereafter. Side effects Common side effects include: - Headache, nausea. - Myalgia, arthralgia. - Dizziness, asthenia. - Constipation, abdominal pain. - Respiratory tract infection, diarrhoea, sinusitis. - Pain in extremity, fatigue, influenza and back pain.

[Rosuva_EZ.pdf - page 3] Drug interactions Concomitant use of Rosuvastatin and Ezetimibe combination with cyclosporine or gemfibrozil is not recommended. Dose modifications are recommended when used with certain antiviral medications, Darolutamide and Regorafenib. Niacin, fibrates and colchicine may increase the risk of myopathy and rhabdomyolysis. Use in pregnancy & lactation Pregnancy: This preparation is contraindicated in women who are or may become pregnant. Lactation: Breastfeeding is not recommended while taking Rosuva EZ. Paediatric use: Safety and effectiveness have not been established in paediatric patients. Geriatric use: No dosage adjustment is necessary solely on the basis of age. Hepatic impairment: Contraindicated in patients with acute liver failure or decompensated cirrhosis. If serious hepatic injury with clinical symptoms and/or hyperbilirubinaemia or jaundice occurs, therapy should be discontinued. Renal impairment: In patients with severe renal impairment (creatinine clearance less than 30 ml/min/1.73 mÂ²) not on haemodialysis, the recommended starting dosage is 5 mg/10 mg once daily and should not exceed 10 mg/10 mg once daily. Overdose In case of overdose, treatment should be symptomatic and supportive, with monitoring of liver function tests and CK and implementation of appropriate supportive measures.

How this medicine works (pharmacology) MUPS (Multiple-Unit Pellet System) refers to modified-release coated multiparticulates or pellets compacted into tablets. In Seclo MUPS tablets, omeprazole-containing pellets are coated with a polymer to protect the drug from gastric acid and to allow release in the small intestine. Omeprazole is a proton pump inhibitor that suppresses gastric acid secretion by specific inhibition of the H+/K+-ATPase enzyme system at the secretory surface of the gastric parietal cell. MUPS ensures rapid and uniform gastric emptying of pellets and uniform drug dissolution in the gastrointestinal tract, facilitating consistent and controlled pharmacological action.
